article.headline: 'Just too much Katie Smith'
article.linkText: Smith's season-high 34 lead Lynx past Monarchs in OT
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Sacramento Monarchs coach John Whisenant was
succinct in explaining his team's loss to Minnesota on Sunday.

"Just too much Katie Smith," he said.

Smith scored a season-high 34 points to lead the Lynx to an
83-73 overtime victory over Sacramento.

"That's what superstars and Olympians do. She seems to wait to
play spectacular against us," said Whisenant, who watched as Smith
hit 12 of 22 shots -- including six 3-pointers -- to lead the Lynx to
their fourth win in their last five games.

Smith has averaged 24 points in three games against Sacramento
this year, while scoring 16.9 against the rest of the league.

"Katie knows what she is capable of doing and what this team
needs her to do," said Lynx coach Suzie McConnell Serio. "We
needed to get her the basketball tonight."

Minnesota scored the first 10 points in overtime, including
3-pointers by Smith and Amanda Lassiter. The Monarchs were 1-for-8
from the floor in overtime after making 51 percent of their shots
in regulation.

"Our defense led to a lot of opportunities on the offensive
end," said Lynx center Nicole Ohlde, who scored nine points and
grabbed four rebounds after being limited to just one minute in the
first half because of two quick fouls.

Lynx center Vanessa Hayen also scored nine points and had a
seven rebounds in 20 minutes, but left the game with 9:53 remaining
after a hard foul sent her to the floor. She sustained a head
injury on the play and was scheduled for a CAT scan Monday, but
team officials described her status as "day to day."

Tangela Smith's 19 points paced the Monarchs, seeking
consecutive road victories.

"We had our opportunities, but couldn't sustain any lead that
we got," said Monarchs center Yolanda Griffith, who had 18 points
and six rebounds. "Every time I thought we were starting to take
the momentum away from them, they had a big shot or got a big stop
on defense."

Minnesota had a chance to win it in regulation, but Lassiter's
3-pointer was off the mark at the buzzer, sending the game to
overtime tied at 71.

Katie Smith scored 20 in the first half, hitting seven of her
first nine shots and four 3-pointers to guide the Lynx to a 36-31
lead at the break.

"Katie Smith was huge tonight," Tangela Smith said. "It
seemed like every time they needed a shot, she was there to knock
it down. When she's playing that well, there's not much you can do
against her."
